[3] Taiwan
Date: Wed 1 Apr 2020 6:25 PM EDT
Source: Public Broadcasting Service (PBS) News Hour [abridged, edited]
https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/taiwans-aggressive-efforts-are-paying-off-in-fight-against-covid-19


Abridged and edited/summarized from a 10-minute interview:

We look now at a COVID-19 success story. Taiwan is just off the coast of mainland China. Millions travel between Taiwan and the Chinese mainland. Johns Hopkins University predicted Taiwan would have the 2nd most COVID-19 cases in the world. But, today [1 Apr 2020], there are 80 countries and territories with more than Taiwan's 329 cases.

Taiwan is only 80 miles [about 50 mi] off the coast of mainland China. When Johns Hopkins modeled COVID-19, it predicted Taiwan would have the 2nd highest number of cases. That prediction didn't become reality. Taiwan has succeeded at containing COVID-19 starting at arrival.

A Taiwanese returning to Taiwan from the UK: on arrival, she was given a form to monitor her temperature in the next 14 days. [She] told authorities she'd had a cough in the last 2 weeks, so security escorted her to secondary screening. She had her temperature taken and she filled out forms consenting to new regulations and providing recent medical history. And she got a COVID-19 test at the airport. Taiwan uploads these results into its national healthcare database to create a kind of coronavirus database that everyone has to enrol in.

They have to register first online. They are sent a text message that has to be shown on arrival at the airport. But that's where government tracking begins. After her bags are disinfected, her ride home is by herself in a government-provided taxi. She is not permitted to take public transport. The government stays in touch during a mandatory 2-week quarantine.

[Another returning Taiwanese who arrived from Australia on 22 Mar 2020] said that on the 1st day, they immediately phoned him, almost within the hour he arrived home in addition to several text messages. "Welcome back to Taiwan. This is the CDC. We're just checking to see if you're OK."

Everyone who arrives in Taiwan today is tracked by cell phone to make sure they stay at home. Taiwan's Center for Disease Control tries to make the 14-day quarantine easy. Someone from CDC verified where he lived and arrived within 4 minutes. He was given a packet of masks, 14 masks in the packet exactly,1 for each day of quarantine.

Taiwan was able to take all of these steps because it learned lessons the hard way. The SARS outbreak was a wake-up call for Taiwan, and they learned a lot from it. Dr Steve Kuo is the former head of Taiwan's CDC and led the SARS taskforce in 2003 when the SARS epidemic made hundreds of Taiwanese sick and killed more than 70, the 3rd highest tally in the world. The very next year [2004], authorities prepared for the next crisis. That preparation allowed Taiwan's CDC to detect the COVID-19 threat before the Chinese government announced it.

They picked up the signal that there was some strange outbreak in the Wuhan area at the end of the last year [2019] from social media networks. They sent 2 medical doctors to Wuhan from Taiwan CDC to get a better understanding of what happened there, and 5 days later, on 20 Jan 2020, the government decided immediately to set up and activate the central command centers.

That centralized command center launched border restrictions before almost anyone else, set local quarantine rules, and turned to technology. One phone app allows Taiwan residents to find stores with masks in stock. Another app provides information on all of those who are COVID-19 positive, where they have been, and their case history. And the government made sure it had enough medical equipment.

After the SARS outbreak, there was a law to require hospitals to have a stockpile of all medical supplies for 30 days.

Today [1 Apr 2020], Taiwan announced that it would donate 10 million masks to medical workers around the world, 2 million to the US.

[byline: Nick Schifrin]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Reviewing the Taiwanese experience with the COVID-19 pandemic up to the present is a testimony to "doing it right". From the start, the Taiwanese took the approach of containment, complete contact tracing, and quarantine with active monitoring. So far it seems to have worked. One can safely say that so far they have managed to hold off large outbreaks for 3 months, knowing that it could very quickly happen. It is a lesson to be learned in how to address a potential pandemic organism. And as a not so small note, it was Taiwanese colleagues who alerted us to the Weibo chatter on the pneumonia outbreak in Wuhan on 30 Dec 2019, which led to our 1st post on the subject. - Mod.MPP

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Taiwan: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7174769,193

