[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 outside China now totals 204. This includes 18 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 60 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 from the Southeast Asia region, 21 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 51 countries (including 16 territories) from the Americas region, and 44 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

The Americas region is reporting 25 737 new cases (in the past 24 hours) of which 87.7% were reported by the USA, followed by Canada (5.4%) and Brazil (1.3%). The European region continues with rapid transmission, having confirmed 40 266 (55.4%) new cases and 3395 (81.1%) deaths in the 24 hours since the last WHO update, with Italy accounting for 10.1% of newly confirmed cases, Spain for 16.3% of newly confirmed cases, Germany for 13.5% of newly confirmed cases, and France for 18.6% of newly confirmed cases (bringing the total of these 4 countries accounting for 58.6% of newly confirmed cases in Europe, down from 62.3% yesterday (31 Mar 2020). In the Eastern Mediterranean region, Iran reported 3111 new cases representing 79.1% of the regional newly reported cases. Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, and Qatar represent 4.4%, 2.8%, and 2.2% respectively. In the African region, Algeria reported 25.4% of the newly reported cases in the past 24 hours and South Africa and Burkina Faso reported 9.4% and 5.2% respectively of the newly reported cases in the region. In the Western Pacific region, The Philippines reported 36.6% of the newly confirmed cases followed by Australia at 23.7%; Japan reported 15.3% of the total (excluding China), followed by Malaysia with 9.5%. In South East Asia, India reported 58.9% of the newly reported cases followed by Thailand with 25.7% and Indonesia with 11.9%, but a caution as only Indonesia and Myanmar reported newly confirmed cases yesterday (31 Mar 2020).

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases reported outside of China, by date of report and WHO region through [1 Apr 2020], at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and now the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA but other countries are following suit. The curve showed a lowering probably related to inconsistent reporting over the weekend and one suspects it is rebounding with today's reports.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: it is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have at times significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and, depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
